  "prompt": "Minecraft: How do you re-generate chunks with MCEdit?",
  "response": "Unfortunately, MCEdit, in its classic form, **does not have a built-in, direct \"re-generate\" feature** to instantly recreate a chunk using the world's seed like Minecraft itself. MCEdit primarily focuses on editing and manipulating existing blocks and structures, not procedural generation.\n\nHowever, you can achieve a similar result through a workaround involving deletion and potentially external tools:\n\n**Workaround using MCEdit (Partial Regeneration):**\n\n1.  **Open your world in MCEdit:**  Load the level.dat file from your Minecraft world save folder.\n\n2.  **Select the Chunk(s):**  Use the chunk selection tool (usually the green chunk grid icon) to select the specific chunks you want to \"regenerate.\"  Make sure to select the *entire* chunk vertically (from bedrock to build limit).\n\n3.  **Delete the Selected Chunks:** Press the \"Delete\" key or use the \"Delete\" button in the MCEdit interface.  This will remove the chunk's data from the MCEdit world. **Important:** This *completely erases* the chunk's data within MCEdit's representation.\n\n4.  **Save the Changes:**  Click the \"Save\" button to write the modified world data back to your level.dat file.\n\n5.  **Open the World in Minecraft:** Start your Minecraft game and load the world.\n\n**What happens in Minecraft?**\n\n*   When Minecraft loads the world, it will encounter the missing chunk data. If the chunk has *never* been generated before (i.e., you haven't explored that area previously *in the current world*), Minecraft will generate it based on the world's seed.  This will give you a \"fresh\" chunk.\n*   **Crucial Point:** If the chunk *has* been generated before *in that world*, Minecraft will load the chunk from the regions files (in the `region` folder) if they exist, *not* re-generate it from the seed.  This means if you had made edits to the chunk before deleting it, those edits are likely still saved in the regions files.\n\n**Limitations and Considerations:**\n\n*   **Previously Generated Chunks:**  The biggest limitation is that this method is only effective for chunks that have *never* been generated in that world.  If they exist in the region files, Minecraft will prioritize loading those files over re-generation.\n\n*   **Region Files:** The region files are stored in your save game folder within the \"region\" folder. If you absolutely need to force re-generation and the chunk has been previously generated, you could theoretically try deleting the corresponding region file(s).  However, **this is extremely risky** and can lead to world corruption.  *Back up your world before doing this!*  Identifying the correct region file(s) that contain the specific chunk(s) you want to regenerate can be tricky.  There are tools that can help with this (see below).\n\n*   **Edge Blending Issues:**  You might experience some visual \"seams\" or abrupt changes in terrain at the borders of the newly generated chunks and the existing chunks, as they may not perfectly blend.\n\n*   **Manual Nature:**  This method is manual and can be tedious if you have a large number of chunks to regenerate.\n\n**Better Solutions (If possible):**\n\n*   **Use an External World Editor:** If possible, consider using a more advanced world editor that *does* have a true chunk re-generation feature. Some options include Amulet Editor, or other modern editors. These editors often have better integration with Minecraft's world generation systems.\n*   **Rollback to a Backup:** If you have a backup of your world from before the problematic chunk was altered, restoring that backup is the safest and most reliable way to revert to the original, seed-generated terrain.\n*   **Create a New World with the Same Seed:** If you only need the same terrain and don't care about existing structures/progress, the easiest option is to create a new world using the *same seed* as your original world.\n\n**In summary, while MCEdit can delete chunks, it doesn't directly re-generate them.  The success of this workaround depends on whether the chunk has been generated previously and whether you are comfortable potentially manipulating region files (with proper backups!). Using dedicated chunk re-generation tools, restoring from a backup, or creating a new world with the same seed are often better and safer solutions.**\n",
